\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 **The Condition:** We assume `θ` is arbitrary (non-exchangeable),
 but `c(x)` is exchangeable (i.e.,
 depends only on `r_obs`).
 Let `c(x) = c(r_obs)`.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 **The Derivation:** We start with the definition of the joint probability of the observed and complete counts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
