\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
`= sum_{x* | Tx*=y*} P(Y=y | X*=x*) * θ_{x*}`
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 **Analyze the inner term `P(Y=y | X*=x*)`:** This is the probability of getting observed counts `y` given a specific complete raw vector `x*`.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
`P(Y=y | X*=x*) = sum_{x | Tx=y} P(X=x | X*=x*) = sum_{x | Tx=y,
 x⪯x*} c(x)`
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since `c(x) = c(r_obs)` is constant for all `x` with counts `y`,
 this sum is `c(r_obs)` times the number of incomplete raw patterns `x` with counts `y` that can be formed from `x*`.
 This number is the number of ways to choose `y_k` items of category `k` from the `(y*_k)` available in `x*`,
 for all `k`.
 This is `
\backslash
prod_k C(y*_k,
 y_k)`.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So,
 `P(Y=y | X*=x*) = c(r_{obs}) 
\backslash
prod_k C(y^*_k,
 y_k)`.
 Crucially,
 this value is **constant** for all `x*` that map to the same `y*`.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 **Substitute back:**
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
`P(Y=y,
 Y*=y*) = sum_{x* | Tx*=y*} 
\backslash
left( c(r_{obs}) 
\backslash
prod_k C(y^*_k,
