\begin_inset Formula $p_{\theta}(x\mid z)p_{\theta}(z)$
\end_inset

.
 Now define a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $x\preceq z$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

,
 read as 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 extends 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\preceq$
\end_inset

-random if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{\theta}(x\mid z) & = & 1[x\preceq z]c_{\theta}(x),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

for a non-zero function 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{x}1[x\preceq z]c_{\theta}(x)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Let's see if we can deduce anything about 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\theta}(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then we get the property 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\theta}(z\mid x)=\frac{p_{\theta}(z)}{\sum_{x\preceq z'}p_{\theta}(z')}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{x}p_{\theta}(x\mid z)=\sum_{x}1[x\preceq z]c_{\theta}(x)=1$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\theta}(x)=\#\{x\mid x\preceq z\}^{-1}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

